Jeremy Corbyn is set to make his debut on Prime Minister's Questions.
Since his election, Mr. Corbyn's PMQ debut has been eagerly awaited.
New Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut on Prime Minister's Questions later today, and for the first time will be working with David Cameron.
Mr Corbyn will ask the first of his six assigned questions shortly after noon, while his performance is likely to be closely watched by the media and MPs.
In a weekly statement, he called for "less drama and more facts".
He also said he could skip a few sessions to leave with his colleagues.
This meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr Corby's leadership, coming after his appointment to the shadow cabinet and his Tuesday speech at the TUC annual congress.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand silently during the singing of the national anthem at a service on Tuesday to mark the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has been met with criticism from a number of Conservative MPs and has been the focus of several front page stories.
Mr. Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has drawn attention
Mr Corbyn's spokesman said he would "stand in respectful silence" and that he would recognise "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain".
However, a member of Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told BBC Two's Newsnight that he would recommend the Labour leader sing the national anthem "regardless" of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to serve in Mr Corbyn's top team, citing differences in economics, defence and foreign affairs, and only less than a sixth of the parliamentary party initially supported him as leader.
The BBC's political correspondent Robin Brant says political differences at work are also "fading" after Mr Corbyn's appointment over his position in the European Union and the government's benefit cap.
Mr Corbyl told the TUC conference that the Labour Party had submitted amended proposals to remove the whole idea of a benefit cap.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the Shadow Secretary for Work and Pensions, said the party was "very clearly" opposed to the government's plans to reduce the limit from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader to face David Cameron in the decade since his election as Conservative leader.
The leader of the Labour Party, who has promised a different approach to politics, claims to have gotten ideas "from the crowd" on questions for Mr Cameron and has received over 30,000 suggestions.
MP Islington North says PMQs are too confrontational and that he will refrain from both "quick answers" and "toothed trade", promising instead to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges faced by young people.
Mr Corbyn claims that Angela Eagle, the shadow trade secretary, will represent him at PMQ when he's not attending  like when Mr Cameron goes abroad.
He also gave up the idea of having other colleagues speak for him from time to time, because he was said to have discussed the whole matter with Speaker John Bercow.
When Mr Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics that was often associated with the PMQ, but admitted a few years later that he had failed.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, PMQs have been seen as a key barometer of leaders' judgment, their leadership of the House and their standing amongst other MPs, although critics have argued that they have become a caricature and far-reaching reforms are needed.
