Metcash launches a rural campaign to fight the Aldi invasion
As Aldi prepares to open two distribution centres and the first of more than 120 stores in South and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream and social media marketing and events such as the Adelaide show.
IGA dealers and suppliers are joining with brands such as Dunsborough-based Simmo's ice cream parlor offering tastings in IGA stores and shop owners selling discounted tickets to the Australian Football League to local customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on September 29th, when the food, liquor and hardware retailer celebrates its annual investor strategy day.
The stakes are high, as South and Western Australia account for almost 30 percent of Metcash IGA's business footprint and generate higher turnover than Metcash IGA's network in the eastern states.
Customers in South and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA stores enjoy a much stronger market share than in NSW, Victoria and Queensland - over 30 per cent in SA and 24 per cent in WA compared to around 14 per cent in the Eastern States.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will take 5 percent of the food market in these two states within 12 months of opening the first stores, which have taken over sales from all existing players, but mainly independent retailers.
In a report this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that retail IGA could lose $360 million in annual sales and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in South Australia and 30 in Western Australia over the next year, generating sales of USD 500 and USD 600 million in each market.
The loss of food sales and volumes in Metcash's fixed price base could cost it around $13 million in pre-tax earnings, Mr Kierath confirmed.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the Eastern States, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although the latest Roy Morgan survey found that IGA shoppers were the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley thinks Metcash food sales will drop 3.8 percent in 2016, 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, and its market share will decline from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, fund manager Hamish Douglass, founder of Magellan Financial Group, said that Melbourne's business lunches could "highly likely disappear within a decade.
Metcash has refused to publicly comment on Douglass's comment.
But it's known that a Metcash board member contacted Douglass last week.
IGA's market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010 and revenues from the Metcash grocery store, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retail stores, have fallen 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operational developments of a speculative shift as sales and earnings are under pressure.
However, wholesalers have gone on the offensive, investing more than $150 million a year to match Coles and Woolworths counter prices on hundreds of products each week, helping IGA retailers re-equip stores by adding fast-growing food and novelty from privateers.
Metcash CEO Ian Morrice says that price matching and store closure programs are catching up and he hopes wholesale will return to core profit growth in 2017 for the first time in four years.
Thanasi Kokkinakis supported by Tennis Australia President Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves the credit for his behavior rather than the criticism.
Thanasi Kokkinakis has become a casualty in the recent uproar over his friend Nick Kyrgios and deserves praise rather than criticism for his behavior, says Tennis Australia president Steve Healy.
Kokkinakis, the younger member of the talented duo often referred to as the "Special Ks", attracted unwelcome attention through an affair with the infamous Kyrgios and Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
Soon after, in a passionate qualifier in Cincinnati, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, Harrison then stated, "Wawrinka should have given one to Kyrgios and I should have given him one too".
While he was last seen smashing a rocket after his cramp was overcome by a possible defeat by Richard Gasquet at the US Open, Kokkinakis was a staunch defender of Healy.
The youngster is currently in Glasgow, where he is competing with Sam Groth for a place in the second two-legged tie behind Bernard Romic in the Davis Cup semi-finals against Great Britain.
"I thought quite intensely that in my opinion Thanasi was a little bit involved in the whole thing", says Healy.
He destroyed his rocket when he lost to a cramp in the US, but he's not the first player to vent his anger on his rocket out of frustration with himself.
But he's really handled himself very well because he's been exposed to very provocative circumstances in the U.S. because of Harrison and so forth, so I think he deserves a lot of credit.
He's got a fantastic team around him, he's got a great family around him, and I think he's been treated a little rough.
He's a very mature 19-year-old man, he works very hard and he fits in very well with the team and so on, he's never had any problems with the other players, he's very respected in the dressing room, he trains hard, he's in amazing shape, he's a very stable and mature young guy and I just think he deserves to be judged on his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision to skip Kyrgios for an important match starting on Friday, stating that a "mutual decision" is the right solution for everyone, but he supports the Canberra native to return to the team as a long-term stable.
"First of all, we want our team to be totally focused on the game and not on all the controversy that has been created around him", says Healy.
And I think Nick's been climbing very fast, as Federer, Murray and other people point out, he's rising fast in the public eye, he's made some terrible mistakes, and he deserves all the criticism he gets, but we're trying to support him, we're trying to help him understand the consequences of his actions, and some time out of the sun when he can think about it, I think is the best solution for the team and also for him.
