Multiple sclerosis: It's not just the medication that counts, but the patient's will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person diagnosed with it needs the care of a number of specialists: a neurologist, a physical therapist, an occupational therapist, a urologist, an ophthalmologist, a psychologist, a psychiatrist, and many others.
But it is not just medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis need counselling if they decide to have a child, and care for these patients also includes social legal counselling, recommendations for housing adjustments, etc.
Yet, this is not enough: the patient himself can have a profound influence on the course of the disease.
The more actively he fights the disease, the longer he can work and the less he needs to make major changes in his lifestyle.
Doctors warn that the passivity of the sick leaves room for the activity of the disease.
For example, regular exercise has been shown to significantly delay the time when the sufferer needs a compensatory aid, such as a cane.
It is important that patients and their families are not subjected to myths, such as that illness automatically leads to a wheelchair.
That is why the website Give Yourself a Chance (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give Yourself a Chance.
The most important person in the care of a person with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
In multiple sclerosis, the double-edged sword is that the earlier the disease is treated, the more the doctor can do something.
That's because we have drugs for multiple sclerosis in the inflammatory stage, when the neurodegeneration process isn't as strong yet.
The sooner we intervene, the better the chances of stopping the disease and delaying its disabling effects, explains MUDr. Eva Medová of the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
Rehabilitation care is very important for people with multiple sclerosis, which usually addresses weakness of the lower limbs or impaired balance.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, reduce swallowing problems, or improve coordination.
"It's really individual, it depends on the specific problems of the patient", says Dr. Martina Kövári, head of the Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic at the Motola University Hospital.
People with multiple sclerosis may have the same disease, but each person manifests it in a slightly different way.
Rehabilitation can't stop the disease, but it can always ease its symptoms.
But physical activity also strengthens the body's immune system, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another benefit of regular exercise is that it helps patients to test their abilities, which builds their self-confidence.
"Exercise also releases endorphins and makes you feel good", notes Dr. Kamila Řasová, Ph.D., of the Rehabilitation Clinic of the Royal Vinohrady University Hospital.
By affecting the physical side, we're affecting the limbic system that's responsible for emotions.
It directly interferes with the psyche and immune system, stabilizing the disease, he adds.
"In the past, these patients were so-called sparing, now we know that they need a targeted load", says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic at the Faculty Hospital in Motol.
The goal of physical therapy is to help a person remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including in the workplace.
Physical therapists work with occupational therapists to provide each person with a compensation device tailored to his or her needs.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They're in a tough situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people are shocked.
They're in shock, panic, fear.
He must respond to a great burden - the loss of health.
With a soul this sick, we're supposed to go to someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them to make them come to the conclusion that even with a disability, a full life can be lived and that multiple sclerosis is not the end of life", says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubert of the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
