In the case of deep-level mining, three-quarters of the coal goes to the municipality and a quarter to the state.
The same ratio will apply to the extraction of radioactive rocks.
The part of the money the State collects on mining fees will be assigned to a specific purpose.
For example, 28 percent will have to go to repair mining damage or to provide a mine rescue service.
The bill was criticized by opposition lawmakers today, who claimed it would harm mining-affected communities and counties.
For example, Michal Kučera (TOP 09 and Mayor) warned that mining companies will no longer want to sponsor municipalities as they have so far, because they will pay higher fees directly to the state budget.
