Kádner and Aulická unsuccessfully proposed to reject the amendment, Kučera wanted to return the law to the government to be finalized.
The explanatory statement states that the mining companies claim that the increase in fees will not affect coal prices because more than 90% of the prices are long-term contracts.
The main consumers such as power plants or boilers should therefore not feel the price increase.
'On the other hand, this fact increases the risk that mining organisations will compensate for the increase in remuneration by trying to reduce their operating costs, which would mainly mean a reduction in the number of employees,' the government admits.
However, it considers that the increase in fees is sustainable in terms of employment.
According to the rapporteur for the amendment Milan Urbana (ČSSD), it is crucial that MEPs know the conclusions on the updated energy concept and especially the government's decision on the limits of coal mining before the law is approved.
