 Sonogenetics, or the control of brain cells by sound waves
This video shows how sound impulses affect the direction in which the fungus moves.
Scientists have bred worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
The tiny bugs change direction when they are hit by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
The pulses work by switching on genetically modified motor neuron cells that are programmed to respond to these ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists can read and record brain activity using light
The researchers said that these worms are a prime example of a new technique called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart, and muscle cells and activate them outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure in which electrodes are inserted into a patient's brain to stimulate the brain, a technique used to treat symptoms of Parkinson's disease, for example.
The worms usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they do when placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplify the ultrasonic waves that then travel through the worms' bodies.
Enhanced ultrasound waves act on TRP-4 ion channels, which are found in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves open and activate these channels, according to a report in the journal Nature Communications.
To control the worms with ultrasonic waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contain TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by microbubbles and carried into the worms, where they activated the modified motor neurons.
The new method is similar in many ways to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light.
Chalasani, however, suggested that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by optical fiber to the desired location in the brain, ultrasound waves can penetrate tissue without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that by using gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases", Chalasani said.
He added that the method could also be used to treat muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
