At their most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve lawmakers will spend two days this week sitting at a 27-foot-long Honduran mahogany table to decide if, after nearly a decade, it's time to raise the key interest rate.
Soaring above them at one end of the central bank's ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the economic interests of the nation above all else.
The Fed has a double mandate from Congress: to maximize American employment and keep prices here stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have recognized that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be the X factor in too close to a predictable decision to be announced on Thursday about whether the U.S. economy is ready to launch on the brink of unprecedented stimulus in the form of near-zero short-term interest rates in place since late 2008.
While most data shows solid economic growth, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed into adding to the volatility by raising its federal funds rate benchmark - even by no more than a mere quarter of a percentage point.
"It's clear that the job market and inflation will be the first and foremost thing to watch", said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to raise the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already gives them sufficient reason to wait", she said.
There's no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is a cause for nervousness in financial markets.
About half of the economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to delay the issue, with the key indicator only about a 30% chance of a raise.
That would indicate a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises rates, only if politicians soften the fall by promising that another hike is out of the question.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep rates quiet this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed raised rates now", he says.
If Fed policymakers did, "they would have to go to the extreme in their policy statement and hold the financial markets in their hands to prevent panic".
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm financial markets by removing uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise rates by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects to see rate increases through the spring and early summer this year despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labour market has shown solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% in the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of rising.
And while inflation continues to run below the central bank's 2% annual target, Fed policymakers say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can and needs to cope with higher rates given the tightness of the labour market", said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to slide late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell as much as 16% below its record high in May as investors worried that a slowing Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has rebounded somewhat this month and the Dow is now losing only nearly 10% of its May high.
The volatile market situation gives Fed policymakers a complex calculation of when to start raising interest rates.
"In the absence of what's happened in financial markets, and reports of weakness in the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, there would be tightening at this meeting", said Stephen D. Oliner, senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now he predicts they'll wait at least a month to get a better handle on the fallout.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what impact this will have on the US economy, and they have almost no data to rely on on the latest developments in China", Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed's primary concerns, so technically it shouldn't be included in their decision making.
But in fact, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The central bank's influence over the last few years has been enormous.
The mere hint of then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might "narrow" their monetary expansion in the marketplace triggered convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interconnected, it is to be expected that Fed officials will monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central bankers and experts to better read the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more art than science", said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy for wealth management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., remarked this month that "the Fed has a history of exaggerating movements in financial markets that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals".
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee's policy-making staff who pushed for rate increases, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The Asian financial crisis led the Fed to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage points over three sessions "despite limited identifiable effects on U.S. growth", Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed reversed the cuts.
The Fed should prioritize financial stability concerns only during a major crisis, such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the Bank of England's rate-setting committee.
The latest surge is nowhere near that level, he said.
"You certainly don't want to be in a situation where you're afraid of rising rates because the markets are upset", said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a double mandate and it doesn't mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should get to the top.
