For moderately obese diabetics, weight loss surgery may be helpful.
The benefits of weight loss surgery for moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes may last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is too early to tell whether moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight-loss surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
"The mortality data take a long time to come across", says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight-loss surgery who wrote the editorial for a new JAMA surgery study.
Weight loss surgery, bariatric surgery, they use different methods to shrink the stomach.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most research has been done on morbidly obese people with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the ratio of weight to height, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates that a person is overweight, and people over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a 2007 study that looked at two types of bariatric surgery -- gastric bypass and gastrectomy -- in the treatment of type 3 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study found that the average BMI of those who underwent the surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who had not received surgery for diabetes remained about the same at 29.
Among the patients who had surgery, 36 percent of the diabetes was completely resolved and 28 percent partially.
In the drug-treated group, diabetes was completely resolved in only 1 percent and partially resolved in only about 2 percent of patients for comparison.
Furthermore, control of blood pressure, triglycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol was shown to be "generally better in the surgical group", the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient' s hemoglobin A1c levels in the blood, which reflect the ongoing blood sugar level in the body.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, say researchers.
After the surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the medication group, this remained at about 8 percent.
But this improved "glycemic control" - reflected in better hemoglobin A1c levels - did not reduce mortality at five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results of the two types of surgery.
After five years, the bypass group lost more weight compared with the gastrectomy group (18.7 kg vs. 14.2 kg), had greater decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent vs. 2.1 percent), and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 percent vs. 16.7 percent).
While the new study shows no improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden that surgery leads to longer lives, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had about a 29 percent greater chance of surviving the next 15 years than the group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not show an improvement in survival among patients after surgery, Blackstone said it is a reassuring result for people with a BMI under 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"This is where this work is critical, because it shows that surgery is safer in the lower BMI group", without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone also says that people and their doctors should start taking weight really seriously once a patient's BMI drops between 27 and 30.
"I think we're waiting too long to let people know how serious the situation is", he says.
I think once you accumulate these genetic changes that tie their bodies to obesity and diabetes, the road back is really hard.
