FriendsFest: a comedy show that teaches us some serious lessons about male friendship.
The absence of similar depictions in various shows is striking, especially given the need for men to open up more desperately than ever before about suicides among young men under 15.
In 2013, it was the single leading cause of death for men aged 20-45 in the UK and remains three times more common in men than in women.
In an effort to address this issue, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) designated 2015 as the Year of the Man, which aims to challenge a culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
At the heart of this struggle lies the friendship to meet this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students with symptoms of depression found that if the affected person had a high enough percentage of friends with "a healthy mood", their chances of recovery doubled.
Similarly, for those who are not depressed, a circle of mentally healthy friends is half the risk of developing mental health problems.
But for friendship to work, of course, it must first be attainable.
In this social media communication with an emphasis on style rather than content, immediate response is often preferred to meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled our need to look stronger, more fun loving and more successful, even when we're actually more isolated.
This superficial success is driven by what psychologists call external values -- money, image, social status -- all at the expense of our true values -- our personal desire for growth and friendship -- which have profound effects on our mental health.
And as a billionaire and game designer recently explained, money really doesn't buy happiness.
The beauty of Friends was the source of this idea for him.
None of the characters were defined by their work, but by their personalities, which shone through friendly interaction.
Joey's humor and Chandler's frequent victimization, the moments of watching football in comfortable chairs, Ross' desire for Rachel, all stem from the realization that yes, men can relate, too, though they usually keep their feelings to themselves.
As one Samaritan worker explained to me, "...my role as a listener of people who feel depressed or suicidal really confirmed to me that even the smallest friendly interactions can make a difference".
The men who contact us often feel unable to communicate with their friends.
The old saying "deal with it" is strong in the sense that you'll be perceived as weak to open up about your problems.
Friends is one of the shows that comes to mind when I try to offer a more long-term compensation mechanism.
It highlights the little moments in male friendship.
As far as my job is concerned, the outsider status on the phone helps people in times of desperation, but long-term support needs to come from a larger circle of friends and family.
So if you're going to Comedy Central's FrendsFest this weekend, why not take your friends for a drink to Central Perk, where the interior will be completely redesigned for the occasion.
Or if you see someone alone at Starbucks, smile at them and say hello.
You never know what a difference your friendship can make.
