How the refugee crisis has shattered the Schengen area.
The German distress beacon, far from disrupting the European crew, is forcing the ship to change course, reports the French newspaper Le Figaro.
The European Union decided on Monday to tackle the refugee problem first: it would rather systematically sort migrants and asylum seekers as they enter the old continent - especially in Greece - than argue over a future allocation of refugees by quota based on numbers that are increasingly moving away from reality.
Six days after European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker asked 25 of the 28 EU countries to reallocate 160,000 refugees, the interior ministers of member states have changed their priorities.
Before we can look at the final destination of refugees, we need to filter out those who are already arriving today and decide the fate of those who are already moving within the Schengen area.
'Effective management of the EU's external borders is essential to managing migration,' stresses the text discussed by ministers in Brussels on Monday.
After the single currency crisis, the EU is finding itself in jeopardy in its next major integration project.
Germany may be surprised, but they're not losing their resolve and increasing the pressure.
It is reinstating border controls, particularly with Austria, but without blocking the flow of asylum seekers into that country.
The central power makes it clear that without it no free movement in Europe is possible.
The fact that Austria and Slovakia joined the measure on Monday was already evidence.
Poland, the Netherlands, Belgium and even France are also considering it, albeit with varying intensity.
Hungary has done this a long time ago.
These exceptional and temporary measures are permissible under the Schengen rules.
It's a domino effect, but the blind can see.
The key issue for Berlin and Paris is now the effective introduction of mandatory entry controls in Greece, southern Italy and also in Hungary for those who have already crossed into the interior.
French Interior Minister Bernard Cazeneuve and his German counterpart Thomas de Maizière discussed the issue intensively in private with their three colleagues from Greece, Italy and Hungary.
This is not a new idea, but it is being implemented with reluctance.
In Italy, according to unofficial statistics, two thirds of newly arrived refugees have already been registered and identified by fingerprinting.
Budapest refuses to establish any point of entry into its territory because it fears more than anyone else that it will have camps to house the refugees at its expense.
The real black hole is still Greece.
More than 200,000 people have landed on its islands off the Turkish coast this year, more than twice the number who have recently arrived in Italy.
Most of them are actual asylum seekers who came directly from Syria after going through overcrowded camps in Lebanon, Turkey and Jordan.
It's a giant gaping hole.
Athens, still in financial ruin and waiting for a new government, has folded its hands.
This is the starting point for the Balkan journey and a source of common concern now for German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orban.
The Juncker Commission has promised to set up checkpoints as soon as possible, but has not given a number or a date.
'The challenges facing Greece are Europe-wide,' EU interior ministers agreed on Monday to mobilise on this front.
The European Union's Frontex border control agency is deployed in the country.
The EU wants to help Greece expand its capacity to receive asylum seekers and strengthen surveillance of the islands.
'Adequate financial resources will be needed,' warns the text submitted to ministers for approval.
In legal terms, they will continue to have the final say in Athens.
The question of a genuine European border guard has not been formally raised, but Europe is getting close to it.
The new emergency situation in the 28th postponed the issue of binding quotas and 160,000 refugees, which had been raised earlier this year by the Juncker Commission and the European Parliament and strongly supported by Angela Merkel and French President François Hollande.
Hungary, Slovakia, the Czech Republic and Poland still don't want to hear about it.
They see it as an attack on their sovereignty.
The number, but not the obligation, was retained in the text approved by a majority of 28 on Monday.
But as a political commitment.
In other words, the process is interrupted.
The only firm pledge includes the redistribution of 40,000 refugees over the next two years, which was already agreed in June during a hectic EU summit, Le Figaro concludes.
