Xi calls for opening up the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open up the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with Tuesday's governance reform.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies", he said of the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group for Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
The promotion of opening-up in the emerging reforms will provide new impetus and vitality, and also provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Steering Group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list regulatory market access, relaxation of border control policy, support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and reorganisation of the resident registration system.
The statement states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and enterprises that are outside the investment limits.
This system will be progressively tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet received any comments from interested parties on the measures in question.
The government will also loosen controls on the powers it delegates to companies, and ensure that companies themselves decide how to run their businesses.
The statement also states that China will allow border regions to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be opened up to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of companies that are financed from abroad and provide them with better services", the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a 'green card', thanks to the optimisation of requirements and simplification of the application process.
The meeting also discussed the safeguarding of lawyers' rights to practice and develop the professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Premier Li Keqiang and senior officials Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
In the Karlovy Vary region, a new hospital may be created.
According to the deputy chief of the Karlovy Vary region, Jakub Paniek (ČSSD), the current capacity of the bed wards of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the wards of the individual hospitals.
But there are also opportunities to expand care in the county.
For example, a surgical unit could have a day surgery centre, where surgical procedures that do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours would be performed according to a set concept.
It is not yet clear which specific hospitals should have day surgery facilities.
The skin department of the Karlovy Vary Hospital could also be a laser centre with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the establishment of an Apalachicola center to care for patients with cerebral palsy who are in a vegetative state.
Such a centre should be centrally established and should be an integral part of the anaesthesia and resuscitation unit.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility in the Island Hospital, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity that appears to be insufficient in Karlovy Vary Region is the post-treatment bed, in particular the bed of the Long-Term Nursing Centre (LDN), which is inadequate in Nejdek and should be closely linked to the acute care beds.
Part of this facility should function as a rehabilitation bed and part as a classic LDN bed, the concept recommends.
He points out that the main hospital in which the following care beds are missing is Karlovy Vary.
There's a place where you could use the abandoned buildings after the centralization.
Last but not least, there are no social health beds in Karlovy Vary Region for the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.
There's a shortage of these beds throughout the republic, so it could be used for other counties as an Alzheimer's center.
The recommendation also states that hospitals should prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds, which will be financed by European grants.
'These are beds that will be built on top of the specialist care areas and will provide a space for transferring patients after surgery, for example after cardiosurgery, neurosurgery, transplantation or other procedures,' the regional concept of bed-care describes.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
